8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 856, L.D. 1321, “An Act to Reform Net
10 Energy Billing by Establishing Limitations on the Programs' Duration and Compensation”
11 Amend the bill by striking out all of section 1 and inserting the following:
12 'Sec. 1. 35-A MRSA §3209-A, sub-§1, ¶C, as enacted by PL 2019, c. 478, Pt. A,
13 §3, is amended to read:
14 C. "Net energy billing" means a billing and metering practice under which a customer
15 is billed for supply charges on the basis of the difference between the kilowatt‑hours
16 delivered by a transmission and distribution utility to the customer over a billing period
17 and the kilowatt‑hours delivered by the customer to the transmission and distribution
18 utility over the billing period, taking into account accumulated unused kilowatt‑hour
19 credits from the previous billing period.'
20 Amend the bill by striking out all of section 3 and inserting the following:
21 'Sec. 3. 35-A MRSA §3209-A, sub-§10 is enacted to read:
22 10. Applicability to projects of more than 500 kilowatts; limitations for projects
23 of 500 kilowatts or less. After November 1, 2025, unless the entity proposing the
24 development of a distributed generation resource is granted a good-cause exemption due
25 to external delays in accordance with subsection 7 or 9, a distributed generation resource
26 may not be used for net energy billing under this section if the nameplate capacity of the
27 distributed generation resource is more than 500 kilowatts.
28 A. Notwithstanding any provision of this section to the contrary, the number of
29 customers or meters is limited to 10 for a shared financial interest in a distributed
30 generation resource with a nameplate capacity of 500 kilowatts or less participating in
31 net energy billing after November 1, 2025 pursuant to this section.
32 B. A customer participating in net energy billing after November 1, 2025 with a
33 distributed generation resource with a nameplate capacity of 500 kilowatts or less
34 pursuant to this section may not, at one time, have a financial interest in more than 5
35 distributed generation resources that have net energy billing arrangements.'
