COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 856, L.D. 1321
1 Amend the bill by striking out all of section 5 and inserting the following:
2 'Sec. 5. 35-A MRSA §3209-A, sub-§12 is enacted to read:
3 12. Renewable energy credits; sale; retirement. If a project sponsor, owner of a
4 distributed generation resource or other entity operating a distributed generation resource
5 participating in net energy billing under this section sells the renewable energy credits
6 generated by the distributed generation resource, the renewable energy credits must be sold
7 and retired in the State.'
8 Amend the bill by striking out all of section 9 and inserting the following:
9 'Sec. 9. 35-A MRSA §3209-B, sub-§10 is enacted to read:
10 10. Renewable energy credits; sale; retirement. If a project sponsor, owner of a
11 distributed generation resource or other entity operating a distributed generation resource
12 participating in the program sells the renewable energy credits generated by the distributed
13 generation resource, the renewable energy credits must be sold and retired in the State.
14 Sec. 10. 35-A MRSA §3209-F is enacted to read:
15 §3209-F. Review of compensation; alteration
16 1. Review of compensation. Notwithstanding the provisions of sections 3209-A and
17 3209-B, the commission may periodically review and by rule alter the amount of
18 compensation that a customer with a financial interest in a distributed generation resource
19 receives as a result of participating in net energy billing under section 3209-A or 3209-B.
20 In making any alteration under this section, the commission shall use a standard or
21 representative distributed generation resource to assess the amount of compensation
22 provided under section 3209-A or 3209-B and shall ensure that any alteration provides a
23 reasonable opportunity for the recovery of reasonable costs, as determined by the
24 commission, and a reasonable rate of return. The commission may not increase any
25 compensation above the lowest amount that would be received under section 3209-B.
26 2. Alteration. Notwithstanding the provisions of sections 3209-A and 3209-B, the
27 commission may modify by rule the requirements under section 3209-A or 3209-B to the
28 extent necessary to allow the State or a distributed generation resource participating in net
29 energy billing under section 3209-A or 3209-B to qualify for federal grants or subsidies
30 that benefit ratepayers in this State.
31 3. Rules. Rules adopted pursuant to this section are major substantive rules as defined
32 in Title 5, chapter 375, subchapter 2-A.'
33 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
34 number to read consecutively.
35 SUMMARY
3366 This amendment does the following.
37 1. It changes the definition of "net energy billing" in the Maine Revised Statutes, Title
38 35-A, section 3209-A, subsection 1, paragraph C to provide that kilowatt-hour credits may
39 be credited only to a customer's electricity supply charges.
40 2. It changes the limitation on the kilowatt-hour credit net energy billing program to
41 provide that, unless a distributed generation resource has met the timing requirements
Page 2 - 132LR1649(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 856, L.D. 1321
412 established for participation in the program, after November 1, 2025, only distributed
423 generation resources with a nameplate capacity of 500 kilowatts or less may be used for
434 net energy billing instead of 20 kilowatts or less as in the bill.
4 3. It clarifies that the limitations on the number of shared financial interest customers
5 or meters and the number of distributed generation resources that have net energy billing
6 arrangements in which a customer may have a financial interest apply to distributed
7 generation resources with a nameplate capacity of 500 kilowatts or less after November 1,
8 2025.
9 4. It requires that if a project sponsor, owner of a distributed generation resource or
10 other entity operating a distributed generation resource with a net energy billing
11 arrangement sells renewable energy credits generated by the distributed generation
12 resource, the renewable energy credits must be sold and retired in the State.
13 5. It allows the Public Utilities Commission to periodically review and by rule alter the
14 amount of compensation that a customer with a financial interest in a distributed generation
15 resource may receive under the kilowatt-hour credit net energy billing and commercial and
16 institutional net energy billing programs.
